-- Hogs Rise as Weights Drop; Cattle Fall: Commodities at Close
-- B y   P a u l   B u r k h a r d t
-- 2012-07-25T22:32:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-25/hogs-rise-as-weights-drop-cattle-fall-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of
24 commodities rose 0.6 percent to 633.92 at 4:11 p.m. New York
time. The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials gained
0.9 percent to 1,546.511.  LIVESTOCK  Hog futures climbed for the first time in a week as
persistent heat through the U.S. Midwest slowed weight gains in
animals being raised for slaughter, limiting pork output. Cattle
prices dropped.  Wholesale pork rose 1.7 percent yesterday to 92.52 cents a
pound, the biggest gain since June 22, U.S. Department of
Agriculture data show. Carcasses at pork plants yesterday
dropped to an 11-month low of 199.12 pounds (90.3 kilograms) on
average, government data show.  Hog futures for October settlement rose 2.8 percent to
settle at 80.2 cents a pound at 1 p.m. on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, the first gain for a most-active contract since July
18. The price has dropped 4.9 percent this year.  Cattle futures for October delivery fell 0.3 percent to
$1.22925 a pound. The price has climbed 1.2 percent this year.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement slumped by CME
limit of 3 cents, or 2.2 percent, to $1.34675 a pound, the
biggest drop since May 23, 2011.  CRUDE OIL  Oil increased after financial shares led U.S. equities
higher and the euro advanced against the dollar for the first
time in six days.  Crude oil for September delivery advanced 47 cents to
$88.97 a barrel on the  New York  Mercantile Exchange. Futures
touched $86.84, the lowest intraday level since July 16. Prices
are down 10 percent this year.  Brent oil for September settlement rose 96 cents, or 0.9
percent, to end the session at $104.38 a barrel on the London-
based ICE Futures Europe exchange.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline slid to a two-week low after U.S. inventories rose
unexpectedly and production reached the highest level since July
2007.  August-delivery gasoline fell 3.19 cents to settle at
$2.7929 a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange, after
touching $2.7298. Gasoline has dropped 5.1 percent this week.
The contract is for reformulated gasoline, or RBOB. The more
actively traded September contract fell 0.96 cent to $2.7162.  Heating oil for August delivery rose 1.96 cents, or 0.7
percent, to settle at $2.844 a gallon. The September contract
gained 2.04 cents, or 0.7 percent, to $2.8467.  NATURAL GAS  Natural-gas futures declined for the first time in six days
in New York on forecasts of moderating temperatures that may
reduce demand for the power-plant fuel.  Gas for August delivery fell 11.7 cents to settle at $3.07
per million British thermal units on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . Gas is up 2.7 percent this year, rebounding after
dropping to a 10-year low $1.902 on April 19. Futures jumped to
$3.187 per million Btu yesterday, the highest settlement price
since Dec. 13.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold gained the most in more than three weeks on
speculation that European leaders may take further steps to tame
the debt crisis.  Gold futures for December delivery rose 2 percent to settle
at $1,612.70 an ounce at 1:43 p.m. on the Comex in New York, the
biggest gain for a most-active contract since June 29.  Silver futures for September delivery jumped 2.4 percent to
$27.466 an ounce on the Comex, the biggest gain since July 3.  On the Nymex, platinum futures for October delivery climbed
0.9 percent to $1,399.40 an ounce. Palladium futures for
September delivery increased 0.6 percent to $565.25 an ounce.  BASE METALS  Copper futures rose for the first time in four sessions on
speculation that European leaders will step up efforts to tackle
the region’s debt crisis.  Copper futures for September delivery increased 0.6 percent
to settle at $3.3745 a pound at 1:18 p.m. on the Comex in New
York. The metal slid 5.1 percent in the previous three sessions.  Zinc, nickel and aluminum advanced in  London , while tin and
lead fell.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cotton futures fell, capping the longest slide in almost
six weeks, on speculation that demand will remain tepid for
supplies from the U.S., the world’s top exporter. Sugar, coffee,
cocoa and orange juice gained.  Cotton for December delivery sank 2.1 percent to settle at
69.51 cents a pound at 2:33 p.m. on ICE Futures U.S. in New
York, capping a three-day slump that was the longest since June
12. Prices are down 24 percent this year.  Raw-sugar futures for October delivery gained 0.3 percent
to close at 23.57 cents a pound on ICE. The sweetener has jumped
25 percent since reaching a 21-month low on June 4.  Arabica-coffee futures for September delivery climbed 0.5
percent to $1.763 a pound in New York, while cocoa futures for
September delivery gained 1 percent to $2,230 a metric ton.
Orange-juice futures for September delivery increased 0.4
percent to $1.102 a pound.  In London futures trading, refined sugar and robusta coffee
retreated on NYSE Liffe. Cocoa advanced.  GRAINS  Corn and soybean futures rebounded on speculation that rain
will miss many growing areas in the U.S. Midwest, heightening
concerns that supplies will decline amid the most-severe drought
since 1956. Wheat also gained.  Corn futures for December delivery gained 1.3 percent to
settle at $7.88 a bushel at 2 p.m. on the Chicago Board of
Trade. The price fell 2.2 percent in the past two days after
rising to a record $8 on July 23.  Soybean futures for November delivery jumped 2.9 percent to
$16.155 a bushel. The price tumbled 6.9 percent in the past two
days after surging to an all-time high of $16.915 on July 23.  Wheat rose on signs that more of the grain will be used in
livestock feed following the corn rally.  Wheat futures for September delivery advanced 2.8 percent
to $9.0325 a bushel. The price has jumped 44 percent since mid-
June.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Paul Burkhardt in New York at 
 pburkhardt@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
